## What's Working Well ✅

1. **Style-level allocation** — The engine correctly groups all 8 sizes of a style together and distributes at the style level before splitting into sizes
2. **Grade multiplier** — A+ stores get proportionally more units
3. **Style DNA matching** — Finding analogous styles from SS25 history (12-21 weeks of data) to infer demand for new SS26 styles
4. **Guardrails** — Max concentration limits are being enforced (no single store dominates)
5. **Story cannibalization** — Detected and applied 0.65x factor for competing colourways
6. **Size curve preloader (N+1 fix)** — The allocation completed without the massive slowdown

## What Needs Attention ⚠️

1. **45.7% utilization** — 54% of received stock is unallocated. This is because the engine is conservative in cold-start mode (style DNA gives lower ROS than actual store data would). As SS26 sales data accumulates, Tier 1-3 will kick in and utilization will increase.

2. **Many zero-qty lines (87%)** — The engine emits zero-qty lines for every store × size combination that didn't receive stock. This is by design (for UI completeness) but inflates the line count.

3. **Low average qty per line (1.17)** — Stock is being spread very thinly. With 127K units across 184 stores and 3,536 styles, each store-style gets ~2 units on average, which gets further split across 6-8 sizes.

## Verdict

> [!TIP]
> **The allocation is working as designed for a cold-start season.** The engine is making intelligent decisions with limited data. Once SS26 starts generating actual sales, the Tier 1-3 demand signals will activate, confidence levels will shift from LOW/MEDIUM toward HIGH, and utilization will climb from 45% toward 70-80%.
